frameDefinitions: An Agent becomes involved in an Issue which has negative consequences for them.

A  Mitigating_situation is presented as occurring against the backdrop of a more preferable situation and a less preferable situation that, while expected, feared, or hoped for, did not or will not occur; the Mitigating_situation is thus, so to speak, sandwiched between a better and a worse situation, both of which are relevant in the discourse.
In this frame an Experiencer experiences an Emotion or is in an Emotional_state.
This frame contains nouns denoting Aggregates of Individuals.
An Entity is presented as having been seen or experienced by a (typically generic and backgrounded)
frameExamples: <t>At least</t> I don’t have to go to school.
An <t><fex name='Agg'>army</fex></t> of postal workers descended on my office.
Susanna Fulton's work is <t>new</t> to me.
listRoleDefinitions: This role identifies the <fen>Issue</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> deals with.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person who is acting to deal with the <fen>Issue</fen>.
This role identifies the time when the Agent acts intentionally.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the intentional act occurs.

The <fen>Mitigating_situation</fen> is the situation that actually occurs. It is presented in a discourse to mitigate the fact that a better situation did not occur - since the role is still preferable to an even worse situation.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences the <fen>Emotion</fen> or is in the <fen>Emotional_state</fen>.
The <fen>Emotion</fen> is the feeling that the <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences.
The <fen>Emotional_state</fen> is the state the <fen>Experiencer</fen> is in.
The <fen>Evaluation</fen> is a negative or positive assessment of the <fen>Experiencer</fen> regarding his or her <fen>Emotional_state</fen>.
This role identifies the people or things that form  the <fen>Aggregate</fen>.
This role identifies the collection of entities that are the <fen>Aggregate</fen>.
A concrete thing or abstract phenomenon or fact that is assessed in terms of how well recognizable it is to a <fen>Cognizer</fen>.
The (typically non-specific and backgrounded) sentient being for whom the <fen>Entity</fen> possesses a specified level of recognizability.
The deviation of the actual level of recognizability of the <fen>Entity</fen> from the level specified by the target.
listRoleExamples: We didn't win $7 million, but at least <fex>I only lost $2 on lottery tickets</fex>.
After two pints, <fex>he</fex> felt a bit better and Ted arrived.
Patients experience <fex>high anxiety levels</fex> at time of admission to hospital.
Her heart was galloping so fast that she felt <fex>quite giddy with happiness</fex>.
Max was feeling <fex>worse than he'd ever felt in his life</fex>.
A crowd <fex>of hoodlums</fex> filled the plaza.
A <fex><t>crowd</t></fex> of hoodlums filled the plaza.
He gave <fex>an address</fex> quite familiar to the chauffeur.
The information used to illustrate the concept is familiar <fex>to the reader</fex>.
He gave an address <fex>quite</fex> familiar to the chauffeur.
